‚ÄúReal doctors‚Äù couldn‚Äôt even produce evidence it ‚Äúdefinitively‚Äù does these things. That‚Äôs part of the problem. We know very little about this virus and what we‚Äôve been doing so far is just a series of educated guesses by smart people who‚Äôs job it is to know about these things. We have a pretty darn good it does because people who are getting it happen and that‚Äôs a pretty darn good indicator. As for sources that say these things they aren‚Äôt exactly hard to find. I‚Äôm don‚Äôt feel compelled to dig through my browsing history to find basic information about the spread of the virus. The news is literally everywhere. 

It‚Äôs the same reason why many doctors were hesitant to endorse hydrochloroquin without testing and approval. They were right to because of the risk of complications and it‚Äôs use for testing those with the virus ended up causing serious complications for many patients. 

This ‚Äúreal doctors‚Äù stuff... smh my head

I shouldn‚Äôt need to explain to you why that argument doesn‚Äôt hold water. This virus is killing young, healthy people. It‚Äôs putting entire  percentages of the people who get it into critical care. It‚Äôs leaving previously healthy people with permanent injuries to their lungs and other organs. It can give young people strokes and present similar to dementia in old people and we don‚Äôt even know why. It can attack the circulatory system. There are a whole host of reasons why this isn‚Äôt being treated like the flu but the bottom line is that this isn‚Äôt the flu. Making these kinds of comparisons between the two, especially if you aren‚Äôt a doctor or a scientist that knows what you are talking about, is juvenile and ignorant.

What do you mean by inert? 

Hundreds of thousands of people have died to this thing, how the hell is that ‚Äúvery rare‚Äù? 

Yes, your immune response is part of how you develop pneumonia which is the main way this thing is killing people. Saying it‚Äôs an autoimmune response that kills people is like saying your key is what makes your car run. Technically an argument can be made that that‚Äôs correct but it‚Äôs such an over simplified explanation that you basically isn‚Äôt saying anything of consequence.

Look, you can disagree all you want but that doesn‚Äôt make you not wrong. I can forgive a lot of diametric viewpoints because people have a right to think and believe whatever the hell they want for the most part but I draw the line at things that actively hurt others. Playing in the dirt is not going to keep an asshole piece of RNA from fucking up your shit and it sure as hell isn‚Äôt going to keep you from communicating said piece of RNA to other people.

Even if you are like me and have trouble finding people to date in the first place then way of thinking will actually be even more harmful. Also, if you‚Äôre this early in dating you don‚Äôt really have much on the line to lose because you haven‚Äôt built much. 

I don‚Äôt want to get preachy but with things closed down now is a good time to reflect on what is so scary about losing someone in this way. We all have different reasons for experiencing what we do and a little introspection can sometimes help us to understand what‚Äôs underneath our fears and anxieties. This can often become the first step to confronting or dealing with them.

I‚Äôm not going to give you advice on how to win over her or anyone else but I will tell you that the more you focus on yourself the better things tend to go. Fixating on another/the other person, even if things go well and you end up together, is not healthy. The cliche ‚Äúwork on yourself‚Äù but comes from the fact that focusing too much on partners or who we see as potential partners is often a sign of things we may have some things about ourselves we need to work on. You are the main character of your own story and when the focus moves solely to someone else, no matter how amazing or wonderful they are or seem to be, we tend to suffer.

Therapy is a largely individual process and a lot of what you get just comes down to who you are seeing. I have found there to be a huge amount of variability in my experience depending on who I am seeing. I‚Äôm not saying that it can‚Äôt be a gendered experience but I will say that how gendered it‚Äôs likely to be is as much a function of which therapist one is seeing than anything else.
It‚Äôs frustrating that trans people are often expected to be an exaggerated caricature of their gender in order to be seen as valid.

You see this is explicitly trans spaces as well where suggestions of hormones therapy is thrown around way too casually. Most people aren‚Äôt saying these sorts of things but it should be called when it is albeit civilly. There‚Äôs no shortage of impressionable and uninformed people.

That hasn‚Äôt been my experience with trans spaces and I‚Äôm sorry it‚Äôs been yours. I keep an eye out for stuff like this because I want to keep an open mind about places that have a tendency to function as echo chambers. I hope I don‚Äôt experience this at any point.

It‚Äôs not that simple. It can feel kind of devaluing to being referred to only by your physical characteristics.

You‚Äôre necessarily wrong about what you‚Äôre saying but there can be other reasons why this is happening. Some people are just so starved for affection that it isn‚Äôt easy to delineate what part of it is making them feel so good about themselves. The confidence boost from receiving that sort of attention may be outweighing any idea of objectification. In a perfect world where everyone is emotionally adjusted it may have come across to them as more objectifying. 

Perhaps they suffer from feelings of low self worth about their appearance and so this sort of attention scratches a special itch for them. Perhaps compliments on appearance are the only compliments of consequence they have experienced in their adult life and so that‚Äôs their default for explaining what would make them feel special. I‚Äôm not saying these are explanations for this specific post but I definitely think the explanation you gave is making an overly narrow interpretation of the issue. 

Personally, I would be over the moon about a compliment about my personality. Given what how often I get complimented I would still be quite happy with being called ‚Äúhot‚Äù even if it might leave a bit of stale taste in my mouth.

I‚Äôm not trying to devalue your experience but as a comparison almost all guys also experience this. Then again some guys like to focus on the best example of they can think of for their weird perception of the female experience and then say, ‚ÄúLoOk HoW MuCh BeTtEr WoMeN HaVe It ThAn MeN!‚Äù

Men who think in the traditionally ‚Äúfeminine‚Äù way about potential partners exist but we are definitely more predisposed to placing value physically attractiveness. It‚Äôs also possible to value both.

Don‚Äôt attack me here because I‚Äôm genuinely asking and trying to understand but it doesn‚Äôt seem to make sense to me delineate between ‚Äúattractive women‚Äù and ‚Äúregular women‚Äù and  then call out other people for making decisions based on appearances. I‚Äôm not saying you‚Äôre wrong about guys but I feel like you‚Äôre kind of doing the same thing to yourself here. I wouldn‚Äôt want to refer to myself as  ‚Äúregular‚Äù because my looks are only a small part of what sets me apart and makes me uniquely attractive. 

On a separate note, a lot of men choose partners based on looks which isn‚Äôt super healthy. They internalize all this crap from media and other guys telling them that the attractiveness of their partner is part of their own worth. It‚Äôs fucked up and it‚Äôs hurtful to the guy just as much as the women he isn‚Äôt properly adjusted to appreciate. It‚Äôs not an excuse but it‚Äôs where a lot of it comes from.

I‚Äôm not defending that behavior or mind set by any means but a lot of men, especially young men, get bombarded with messages that internalize into this type of unhealthy thinking without their consent or even realizing it is happening. It‚Äôs not an excuse but it explains a lot of it without having to demonize.

All the crap me grow up with often gets internalized and messes with their heads in ways it can be hard to deal with. It‚Äôs not uncommon for a man to learn to associate his perceived worth as a partner or potential partner as synonymous with his self worth. As incorrect and unhealthy as this is it most men aren‚Äôt even going to be cognizant of this kind of internalization, especially at a young age.

Maybe what they‚Äôre trying to say, and may be wrong, is that because men are expected to make the first step it also tends to put us in a position where we are expected to ‚Äúprove our worth‚Äù in the same situation. You have to be on your toes not to get rejected by the automatic filter many women seem to have to men who approach them. That being said I think this is an archaic stereotype that oversimplifies both the men‚Äôs and woman‚Äôs experiences but I think that was what they meant. Maybe they are also commenting on the nerve wracking nature approaching can have for many. 

Or they actually feel like there is a need to ‚Äúwalk on eggshells‚Äù which isn‚Äôt very well adjusted. Of course this can be through no fault of one‚Äôs own such as a bad parenting situation or abusive ex but it can also just be from being an asshole.

You are totally not wrong but there is disparity in genders experiences. The asymmetry of the comparison IMO comes in when you look at how guys are expected to approach culturally. Guys can end up in the unfortunate ‚Äúnumbers game‚Äù situation where they‚Äôre having to approach many  women for each single chance to share the actual value of their personality and whatnot. It definitely contributes to the toxicity of the whole thing. I tend to stay away from cold approaching women for this reason. I also have gone periods of years without meeting a single person though but I actually don‚Äôt know if there‚Äôs correlation or not.
I would love to get hit on or complimented by literally any woman as long as it was appropriate. I don‚Äôt have to want to date someone to appreciate them finding me interesting or attractive.

I‚Äôm not going to give any shit because you aren‚Äôt necessarily wrong but I think it‚Äôs important to remember that having this kind of distorted view about experiences that aren‚Äôt your own isn‚Äôt a gendered thing.
You‚Äôre not wrong but I think you‚Äôre taking it a little far. Granted people with this outlook on dating probably need to work on themselves but that description was a bit harsh.
I have happen to the point it tends to serious hampered any genuine and appropriate advances I make.

I think there‚Äôs ways to do it without coming across as flirty because I have been on the receiving end up it before but I have no idea how. On the flip side it can be frustrating not to be able to platonically compliment a woman without it being seen as coming on to them so I get what you‚Äôre saying.

Sometimes people aren‚Äôt the best at signaling their intentions or at interpreting intentions. My two cents is to give people the benefit of the doubt until you know a little more because of how much can be lost in translation especially when expressing interest. I think this is especially true for women who culturally to have less experience in this area. There‚Äôs nothing wrong with saying no if something turns out not to be what you are looking for.
There are plenty of guys who absolutely aren‚Äôt this one dimensional. It isn‚Äôt fair to stereotype an entire gender this way even if they are dudes.
All lot of men just don‚Äôt have the option of being this selective because they‚Äôll just end up never getting a date.

I think that is just a human thing. In my experience most people are interested in more than just what someone looks like unless they are strictly only interested in sex. Approaching just sucks for everyone. I think there‚Äôs plenty of people who would just avoid it altogether if that were a possibility, regardless of gender.

There‚Äôs lots of guys who are interested but just don‚Äôt work that way in regard to chasing or ‚Äúgetting a prize‚Äù. Don‚Äôt get me wrong lots of guys do feel that way but to those who don‚Äôt I feel like it‚Äôs a fair assumption.
